These were the women he knew,<br>
One wore his token,<br>
One bore his daughter,<br>
But only to one was he true.<br>
<br>
These were the loves of the Lord of December,<br>
These were the women he kissed,<br>
The Maiden in White,<br>
The Mistress of Magic,<br>
And the Lady in gray chains of mist.<br>
<br>
The Lord kissed the Maiden in White at his wedding,<br>
The Mistress of Magic looked on,<br>
Stirring inside her,<br>
The seed of his passion,<br>
She left them her gift, then was gone.<br>
<br>
A throne to the Lord from the king as his dowry,<br>
Three priceless jewels from his wife,<br>
Best wishes from bold friends<br>
With whom he hand hunted,<br>
From the mistress of magic, a knife.<br>
<br>
Low burnt the merry red fires of the feasting,<br>
The Lord led the Maid to his bed,<br>
“Do you love me?” she whispered<br>
The lord answered, laughing,<br>
“I love more the crown on my head.”<br>
<br>
“Knave!” spat the Maiden, her eyes fierce with anger<br>
“Betrayed!” sang the knife on the floor,<br>
She snatched up the dagger,<br>
And felt its sharp hunter,<br>
“I’ll see that you use me no more!”<br>
<br>
“You swore to be true” screamed the hilt of the dagger<br>
“You promised that we’d never part!”<br>
Then the Lady in gray,<br>
At the tip of the dagger,<br>
Kissed the Lord deep in his heart.<br>
<br>
These were the loves of the Lord of December,<br>
He cursed them with his final breath,<br>
And cold is the bed<br>
Where the Lord now lies sleeping,<br>
And his lover, the gray Lady, Death.<br>
<br>
Meledi Weaver<br>
Bard of 62 Songs<br>
League of Honour<br>
